df.rename(columns = column, inplace = True)

First of all, in Turkey, the regulation to change the clocks was abolished in 2016. So, in March 2016, clocks moved forward 1 hour. This situation affects our training data while shifting. For this reason, to prevent this effect, we should remove the whole week that clocks move forward because it will be problem while shifting.. The time range should be removed is between 21.03.2016 Monday 00:00 and 27.03.2016 Sunday 23:00. After that, training data created and it can be used for regression.

Comment for question a): If we look at the results which are calculated by MAPE for each period, lag168 and lag48 approach give 3.449 and 8.060 values of MAPE, respectively. MAPE is a measure of prediction accuracy of a forecasting method in statistics. Smaller MAPE values mean higher accuracy. For this reason, MAPE_168 with 3.449% value is more suitable to forecast energy consumption amount for specific date and time rather than MAPE_48 as expected because lag168 consider the same day; altough lag48 consider the different day. As a result, seasonality in terms of day is important for energy consumption. Moreover, in the summary statistics results, standard deviation for lag168 and lag48 are 3.12 and 8.55, respectively. Also, minimum errors are 0.00852 and 0.0095, respectively. On the other hand, on 05.11.2020 and 08.11.2020 at 09 a.m, lag168 and lag48 gives the worst error.

The value is better than lag48 (%8.06) result in part a, while it is worse than lag168 result (%3.44). Moreover, in summary statistic, maximumum error is smaller than both approaches in part a. In the linear regression R^2 value is founded as 0.81, and this shows that linear regression model is highly accurate for this data. Moreover, in residual plot above, the majority of deviations are close to zero. Finally, the linear model can be written as with beta values: Y = 1570.189 + lag_480.309 + lag_1680.643. These beta values are founded above.

In [38]:
#create the train_data
train_c = df.iloc[0:sp_index,:] ; train_c = train_c.reset_index()
train_c = train_c.drop('index', axis = 1)
#create the test_data
test_c = df.iloc[sp_index:,:] ; test_c = test_c.reset_index()
test_c = test_c.drop('index', axis = 1)
#array to hold mape score for each time
test_scores = []
##create dataframe to hold predictions and actual value to plot residuals later
test_hold = pd.DataFrame()
train_hold= pd.DataFrame()
###filter data for each hour,then make regression
for i in range(0,24):  
    if i <= 9: #because of notation, firstly regression is made for between the time 0 and 9.
        train = train_c[train_c['Time'] == f'0{i}:00']; train = train.reset_index(drop=True)
        test  = test_c[test_c['Time']   == f'0{i}:00']; test  = test.reset_index(drop=True)
    if i > 9:
        train = train_c[train_c['Time'] == f'{i}:00']; train = train.reset_index(drop=True)
        test  = test_c[test_c['Time']   == f'{i}:00']; test  = test.reset_index(drop=True)
    #create responses and covariates for train and test
    train_x = train[['lag_48','lag_168']]
    train_y = train[['Consumption Amount (MWh)']]
    test_x = test[['lag_48','lag_168']]
    test_y = test[['Consumption Amount (MWh)']]
    #linear regression
    reg = linear_model.LinearRegression()
    #train the model using the training sets 
    reg.fit(train_x,train_y)
    #prediction
    predictions = reg.predict(test_x)
    predict_train = reg.predict(train_x)
    #add predictions as column with decimal 2.
    test = pd.concat([test, pd.DataFrame(predictions)], axis=1); test.rename(columns={0:'Predictions'}, inplace=True)
    test = test.round({'Predictions':2})
    
    train=pd.concat([train, pd.DataFrame(predict_train)],axis=1); train.rename(columns={0:'Predictions'}, inplace=True)
    train = train.round({'Predictions':2})
    #MAPE Calculation
    test['Absolute_Percentage_Error'] = np.divide(np.abs(np.subtract(test.iloc[:,4],test.iloc[:,5])),test.iloc[:,4])*100
    mape_reg = np.mean(test['Absolute_Percentage_Error'])
    test_scores.append(mape_reg)
    if i <= 9:
        print('Mean Absolute Percentage Error for the Hour' + f' 0{i}:00 with test data: ' +  str(round(mape_reg,3)) + 
              '%')
         
    if i > 9:
        print('Mean Absolute Percentage Error for the Hour' + f' {i}:00 with test data: '+str(round(mape_reg,3)) +
              '%')
    #append results to dataframe which will be used to plotting residuals later
    test_hold = test_hold.append(test)
    train_hold = train_hold.append(train)

Comment for question c): In this question linear regression is made 24 times for each hour differently because it may be that lag48 and lag168 don't have constant beta value for all hours prediction. At first glance, MAPE value for each hour seems appropriate. Mean value of MAPE value of all hours is 4.358%. Although this is slightly higher than result in part b, standard deviation is very low (1,351%). The result is very good for meaningles deviation. If we observe results hourly which are showed at the beginning of this question part (score_df) , MAPE values are approxmately 3.30% at night (00:00 - 07:00). Also, after 6 p.m., MAPE values close to 3.30% again. On the other hand, between working hours, 08:00 and 17:00, deviations are slightly bigger. This is reasonable because consumption increases and it shows fluctuations mostly in working hours. At 13:00 time period, regression gives the worst result with MAPE value 6.685%. Finally, in the residual plot, the majority of deviations are close to zero except outliers.

##create dictionary to hold actual value and predicted value for each hour with dataframe
results = {}
#create array to hold MAPE values of lasso for each hour
lasso_scores = []
#create dataframe to hold coefficients of Lasso for each hour with dataframe
##column name for coef dataframe
columns = np.delete(np.array(df_wide.columns), [0,1,2])
coef = pd.DataFrame(columns = columns)
#converting date to datetime to split train and test
df_wide['Date'] = pd.to_datetime(df_wide['Date'])
##create dataframe to hold predictions and actual value to plot residuals later
test_hold_lasso = pd.DataFrame()
train_hold_lasso= pd.DataFrame()
for i in range (0,24):
    if i <= 9: #because of notation, firstly regression is made for between the time 0 and 9.
        ##hour filtering   
        train = train_wide[train_wide['Time'] == f'0{i}:00']; 
        test = test_wide[test_wide['Time'] == f'0{i}:00'];
        
        #create responses and covariates
        x_train = train.iloc[:,3:]
        y_train = train["Consumption Amount (MWh)"]
        #test
        x_test = test.iloc[:,3:]
        y_test = test["Consumption Amount (MWh)"]
        ##regression
        
        alphas =  np.array([10**i for i in range(-4,1)]) 
        lassocv = LassoCV(alphas=alphas,cv=10, max_iter=100000)
        ##fitting train data
        lassocv.fit(x_train,y_train)
        
        #train predict
        predict_train = lassocv.predict(x_train)
        
        #add predictions as column with decimal 2.
        train_lasso=pd.concat([y_train.reset_index(drop=True), pd.DataFrame(predict_train)],axis=1); train_lasso.rename(columns={0:'Predictions'}, inplace=True)
        train_lasso = train_lasso.round({'Predictions':2})
        
        
        ##predicting test
        predictions = lassocv.predict(x_test)     
               
        #add predictions as column with decimal 2.
        results[i] = pd.concat([y_test.reset_index(drop=True), pd.DataFrame(predictions)], axis=1); results[i].rename(columns={0:'Predictions'}, inplace=True)
        results[i] = results[i].round({'Predictions':2})
        
        # Calculate absolute percentage error and add as column
        results[i]['Absolute_Percentage_Error'] = np.divide(np.abs(np.subtract(results[i].iloc[:,0],results[i].iloc[:,1])),results[i].iloc[:,0])*100
        # to observe later save MAPE value in array
        mape_lasso = np.mean(results[i]['Absolute_Percentage_Error'])
        lasso_scores.append(mape_lasso)
        # add coefficients to df
        #coef[f'{i}.Hour'] = lassocv.coef_
        coef.loc[f'{i}. Hour'] = lassocv.coef_ 
        
        #append results to dataframe which will be used to plotting residuals later
        test_hold_lasso = test_hold_lasso.append(results[i])  
        train_hold_lasso = train_hold_lasso.append(train_lasso)        
    if i > 9:
        ##hour filtering   
        train = train_wide[train_wide['Time'] == f'{i}:00']; 
        test = test_wide[test_wide['Time'] == f'{i}:00'];
        
        #create responses and covariates
        x_train = train.iloc[:,3:]
        y_train = train["Consumption Amount (MWh)"]
        #test
        x_test = test.iloc[:,3:]
        y_test = test["Consumption Amount (MWh)"]
        ##regression
        alphas =  np.array([10**i for i in range(-4,1)])
        lassocv = LassoCV(alphas=alphas,cv=10, max_iter=100000)
        ##fitting train data
        lassocv.fit(x_train,y_train)
        #train predict
        predict_train = lassocv.predict(x_train)
        #add predictions as column with decimal 2.
        train_lasso=pd.concat([y_train.reset_index(drop=True), pd.DataFrame(predict_train)],axis=1); train_lasso.rename(columns={0:'Predictions'}, inplace=True)
        train_lasso = train_lasso.round({'Predictions':2})
        
        
        ##predicting test
        predictions = lassocv.predict(x_test)
        #add predictions as column with decimal 2.
        results[i] = pd.concat([y_test.reset_index(drop=True), pd.DataFrame(predictions)], axis=1); results[i].rename(columns={0:'Predictions'}, inplace=True)
        results[i] = results[i].round({'Predictions':2})
        # Calculate absolute percentage error and add as column
        results[i]['Absolute_Percentage_Error'] = np.divide(np.abs(np.subtract(results[i].iloc[:,0],results[i].iloc[:,1])),results[i].iloc[:,0])*100
        # to observe later save MAPE value in array
        mape_lasso = np.mean(results[i]['Absolute_Percentage_Error'])
        lasso_scores.append(mape_lasso)
        # add coefficients to df
        #coef[f'{i}.Hour'] = lassocv.coef_
        coef.loc[f'{i}. Hour'] = lassocv.coef_ 
        #append results to dataframe which will be used to plotting residuals later
        test_hold_lasso = test_hold_lasso.append(results[i])
        train_hold_lasso = train_hold_lasso.append(train_lasso)
lasso_mape_df = pd.DataFrame(lasso_scores, columns = ['MAPE'])

Comment for question d) In this question lasso regression is implemented. At first glance, MAPE values for each hour period seems appropriate. Moreover, they seems better than even results in part c. Mean value of all hour MAPE is 2.687% and standard deviation is 1.254%. These results very good for accuracy. Minimum deviation is resulted in the data which covers time period 20:00 (%1.51) while maximum deviation is resulted in the time period 14:00 (%4.68). The seasonality effect like in part c, shows itself in this question again. In working hours, fluctuation increases. This causes an increase in deviation and MAPE. Besides, in coef dataframe, coefficient or values of beta for lasso regression exist. Minus sign means that the lag period affect inversely the consumption. Also, absolute value of coefficient shows the effect size. Coefficient has bigger absolute value can be considered as significant. Moreover, in the residual plot, the majority of deviations are close to zero except outliers. Among approaches conducted till part d, lasso regression gives the best results with the mean value of 2.687%.
